@danlesac Yeah that sounds stupid af tbh. Maybe they're planning to integrate a bridge onto Eth at some point? Total conjecture on my part though. 

@veve_official did similar with their bespoke marketplace migrating onto Immutable X. Their app marketplace is fiat first, kinda...$1 = gem.

@danlesac As for the "why use ethereum" - I guess market penetration? I don't know, I don't run the Brits lol. If their end game is to make something enduring then it makes sense to place it onto the most supported network. Adoption of other L1 chains pales in comparison

@danlesac Possibly an issue with a watered down 'tweet take' on something complicated. It reads like it implies Polygon just sends the transactions back to Eth to be processed in the same way as native L1 transactions. Which isn't the case. Rollups are very efficient

@danlesac Polygon is proof of stake which is like 1000x more energy efficient than the eth proof of work. It then uses a roll up standard to send all of these transactions in one block to the main ethereum network - blocks that would have been mined anyway. It's a good scaling solution.
